<subSubSection pageId="9" pageNumber="161" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1283,1958]" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,322,1427,1453]" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Male (
<figureCitation box="[408,495,1427,1454]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 37</figureCitation>
). Medio-apical margin of clypeus (
<figureCitation box="[904,989,1427,1454]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
) with deep notch, clypeus with sparse punctures; vertex (
<figureCitation box="[358,438,1463,1490]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 39</figureCitation>
) with moderate and shallow punctures; OOD: POD: OCD: Od = 1: 2.54: 1.57: 1.06; width of head 6× Od, ocelli (
<figureCitation box="[407,536,1499,1526]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Figs 38, 39</figureCitation>
) conspicuously enlarged, posterior ocelli distinctly convex in frontal view (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 38</figureCitation>
); pronotum (
<figureCitation box="[331,413,1535,1562]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 40</figureCitation>
) without anteriorly transverse carina and sparsely punctate; lateral side of pronotum (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 41</figureCitation>
) ventrally densely striate; dorsal surface of propodeum (
<figureCitation box="[815,897,1571,1598]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 42</figureCitation>
) largely densely strio-punctate; L 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1273,1305,1590,1604]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Tap4</subScript>
/ L 
<subScript attach="left" box="[1334,1367,1590,1604]" fontSize="6" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Tap5</subScript>
about 1 or a bit less; each of T1–T6 subapically with a row of punctures and medially absent forming incomplete groove, rest surface with very sparse punctures; T7 (
<figureCitation box="[658,741,1643,1670]" captionStart="FIGURES 37–43" captionStartId="10.[151,264,1436,1460]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,183,1412]" captionTargetId="figure-17@10.[151,1436,181,1412]" captionTargetPageId="10" captionText="FIGURES 37–43. Komarowia mongolina, ♂. 37. Habitus, dorsal view; 38. Head, frontal view; 39. Vertex, dorsal view; 40. Pronotum, dorsal view; 41. Pronotum, lateral view; 42. Propodeum, dorsal view; 43. T7, dorsal view." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.6641330" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/6641330/files/figure.png" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">Fig. 43</figureCitation>
) with deep and moderate punctures, apex smooth and with a V-shaped notch, tipped lobes broadly rounded.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="9.[151,1437,1283,1958]" pageId="9" pageNumber="161">
Female. Head smooth and with a few sparse punctures; clypeus apically with sparse and minute punctures; scape of antennae subequal to the length of F1–F3, and length of F5 0.25× length of scape; pronotum with sparse minute punctures medially, punctures on anterior and lateral surface denser and deeper than those on median; dorsum of propodeum with sparse and deep punctures; T1 and T2 laterally with sparse and minute punctures; each of T2–T6 subapically with a row of punctures and medially absent forming incomplete groove. No male specimens were collected in our study, and the description is referred to Guiglia (1973) and 
<bibRefCitation author="Boni Bartalucci, M." box="[1057,1332,1895,1922]" pageId="9" pageNumber="161" pagination="1205 - 1308" refId="ref15254" refString="Boni Bartalucci, M. (2004 b) Tribe groups of the Myzininae with special regard to the Palaearctic taxa of the tribe Meriini (Hymenoptera, Tiphiidae). Linzer Biologische Beitrage, 36 (2), 1205 - 1308." type="journal article" year="2004">Boni Bartalucci (2004b)</bibRefCitation>
.
</paragraph>
